      <hedline>
        <hl1>Hope and Fear on Social Security</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Herbert Barchoff, who served on President's Council of Economic Advisers in Truman administration, opposes privatizing any part of Social Security, saying it would further inflate stock market</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Although I applaud your May 29 editorial ''Campaigning on Social Security,'' there is yet another cogent reason for not privatizing any part of the program.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Although I applaud your May 29 editorial ''Campaigning on Social Security,'' there is yet another cogent reason for not privatizing any part of the program.</p>
        <p>The infusion of many billions of dollars would further inflate the stock market. A revival of ''irrational exuberance'' feeds on itself. The consequences could be disastrous.</p>
        <p>HERBERT BARCHOFF  New York, May 29, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer served on the President's Council of Economic Advisers in the Truman administration.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
